<!DOCTYPE html> <html> <body> <p>For production, I decided that my databases will be deployed to the cloud and managed by MongoDB themselves. This decision was taken because I did not want to manage and scale my own database. MongoDB atlas provides both automatic horizontal and vertical scaling for their clusters.<br>The cluster that I have chosen is the free tier of cluster with shared ram and 512MB of storage. The server is located in Paris and is provided by AWS</p><p><img src="https://portfolio.drieam.app/api/public/v1/blobs/545ea1b8-b9c6-4fdf-9e1d-cab50ed05fbf/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBMnNlQXc9PSIsImV4cCI6bnVsbCwicHVyIjoiYmxvYl9pZCJ9fQ==--6308fd25ed55d27551b5e7af69fa07409b8e8080/image_2024-03-28_091123408.png" data-key="t673zch3rk4ea6u46y8grnwb6gut"><br>These parameters are quite weak, but for a proof of concept, it is good enough. Load testing will not be conducted on the production database, but on a local Kubernetes cluster.<br><br>Below is a screenshot of a connection to the production cluster made by a low-privilege production account<br><img src="https://portfolio.drieam.app/api/public/v1/blobs/545ea1b8-b9c6-4fdf-9e1d-cab50ed05fbf/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBMjRlQXc9PSIsImV4cCI6bnVsbCwicHVyIjoiYmxvYl9pZCJ9fQ==--b2fb937cb310736e889bc343b7c6d1dd6a1b95b0/image_2024-03-28_091342393.png" data-key="wjsaydcy5qm333zadspbq5xxggya"></p> </body> </html>